    <span class="post-title">&#129522; How to Get Whatever You Want</span>
    <span class="post-date">May 20th 2026</span>
  </div>
  <div class="post-body">
    <p>
      <strong>Ask!</strong>
      <br>I’ve been watching an old Jim Rohn talk called
      <a
        href="https://youtu.be/uOcKF-aLHyw"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
        >How to Get Whatever You Want</a
      >.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>1. Asking is the beginning of receiving.</strong> It starts
      a process you can't fully see, mental and emotional. Like flipping a
      switch and hearing machinery kick on somewhere in the back. You
      don't need to understand the wiring to use the switch.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>2. Receiving isn't the problem. Failing to ask is.</strong>
      His line that got me: "good worker, poor asker." The guy who shows
      up every single day but never once wrote his goals down. Hit a
      little too close.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>3. Abundance is an ocean, not a ration.</strong> Success
      isn't behind a window that sells out before you reach the front. The
      ocean is right there. The only question is whether you walked up
      with a teaspoon or a bucket. Time to trade the teaspoon for a
      bucket.
    </p>
    <hr class="post-divider" />
    <p>Then he splits asking in two.</p>
    <p>
      <strong>Ask with intelligence</strong>: don't mumble. How wide, how
      high, how soon, what size, what color, how much. The sharper you
      describe a goal, the harder it pulls you, like a magnet.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Ask with faith</strong>: believe you'll get it the way a kid
      believes, before adulthood trains you to be skeptical.
    </p>
    <p>
      The whole hour folds into one sentence I'm keeping:
      <em>make plans like an adult, believe in them like a child.</em>
      He says give it 90 days. You can always go back to the old way. The
      world admires the doers.
    </p>
    <p>
      The entire lecture builds to a single-word strategy:
      <strong>Ask</strong>. It sounds basic until he unpacks why most
      people completely fail at it.
    </p>
  </div>
